    id: 6, day: 6,
    title: "Renewing Your Mind Around Food",
    subtitle: "Replacing lies with truth",
    readTimeMin: 9,
    theme: "identity",
    scripture: { verse: "Do not be conformed to this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind.", reference: "Romans 12:2 (NKJV)" },
    prayer: "Father, Your Word promises I can be transformed by the renewing of my mind. Today I surrender the food beliefs that have held me captive — the rigid rules, the shame, the lies diet culture has sold me. Write Your truth on my heart instead. Amen.",
    content: `You carry a set of food beliefs that were handed to you — by your family, your culture, your past diets, and the media. Many of these beliefs are lies. And lies, repeated long enough, feel like truth.

Here are some common food lies: "I have no willpower." "I'll start over on Monday." "I already ruined today, so I might as well keep going." "I don't deserve to feel good in my body." "This is just how I am."

Romans 12:2 calls us to something radical: don't be molded by the patterns of this world (including diet culture, comparison, and shame). Instead, be transformed — metabolized into something new — through the renewing of your mind.

**CBT Skill: Cognitive Restructuring**

The CBT equivalent of "renewing the mind" is called cognitive restructuring — identifying distorted thoughts and replacing them with accurate ones.

Common food-related distortions:
- **All-or-nothing thinking**: "I ate one cookie, so today is ruined." → Truth: "One cookie is just one cookie. My next choice is still my choice."
- **Catastrophizing**: "If I can't stick to this perfectly, I'll never change." → Truth: "Progress is not linear. Setbacks are part of the process."
- **Mind reading**: "Everyone at the party is judging what I eat." → Truth: "People are far more focused on their own food than on mine."
- **Emotional reasoning**: "I feel fat, therefore I am fat and hopeless." → Truth: "Feelings are not facts."

**The Practice**

When a negative food thought appears, don't just dismiss it — replace it. Ask: Is this thought true? Is this thought helpful? What would I say to a dear friend who had this thought?

Transformation begins in the mind. Feed it truth.`,
